details.value: Anna Ebin or Eybin, a fifteenth-century Augustinian nun, and provost of her convent in Pillenreuth (near Nuremberg) from 1461-1476, was a prolific scribe and compiler of devotional books. Although only four books have survived in which her hand has been identified, in one of these books she is said to have written “gar und vil puecher dem convent […] die ungezelt sind” (very many books for the convent that are countless).

Anna Schott (ca. 1450-after 1521), daughter of the Strasbourg mayor Peter Schott (1427-1504) and sister of the jurist, theologian, and humanist Peter Schott (1460-1490), can be traced in Strasbourg as a Dominican nun of the convents St. Agnes and St. Margaret and St. Agnes (from 1475). She was extensively educated. During the fire of the Strasbourg city library in 1870, a manuscript written by her around 1500 (.Historia sanctorum") was lost (Schlechter, Schott, p. 467). In Schwarzach 19, it is the second known Anna Schott manuscript; it was considered lost (Cowie/Cowie (see Lit.), p.753).

Professional, laywoman scribe
Hatzlerin was a scribe in Augsburg who has nine signed surviving manuscripts. She lived with her brother, a notary, and was commissioned to produce books for wealthy citizens. The article concludes with a descriptive catalog of her nine known manuscripts. 
Clara Hätzlerin (* around 1430 in Augsburg ; † probably 1476 or the following year) was a hired clerk in the 15th century. She is the only woman documented who made handwritten copies of German codices for a fee . It can be proven in Augsburg tax books between 1452 and 1476. [1]
Clara Hätzlerin came from a family of notaries that was typical of Augsburg at the time. Her father Bartholomew is known to have been a so-called letter writer who, as a representative of rich citizens, regulated their legal rights. He is documented in tax books between 1409 and 1443 as well as through an entry in the Augsburg Missive Book and as a witness in a mortgage note from Marx Lang. [2] When Bartholomew died in 1444/45, Bartholomew's eldest son, who is documented as a notarius publicus between 1451 and 1496, took over the office and thus also the tax liability.
The most conclusive refutation is provided by Augsburg tax books, which show that Clara paid taxes in her father's house for 24 years, something she could never have done as a nun, since in this case her assets would have gone to the monastery. [4]
The profession of paid and professional writer is a phenomenon of the 15th century, a time in which the writing industry flourished and the need for everyday literature increased. The city of Augsburg played a pioneering role in this area, as it has a list of over 30 proven payroll clerks. Hired scribes were mainly laypeople who produced cheap copies of manuscripts for the public by copying them by hand and were no longer, as was usual up until then, members of the clergy who had specialized in the artistic design of magnificent manuscripts. In addition to Clara Hätzlerin, the calligraphers Heinrich Molitor and Heinrich Lengefeld and Konrad Bollstatter also belonged to this group of people. [5] It was quite common for professional writers to work part-time in public, legal or administrative writing. Clara Hätzlerin also worked in the law firm of her father Bartholomäus Hätzler and her brother of the same name. As a part-time job , she made handwritten copies of commissioned books. Some manuscripts from her pen, which are mainly practical manuscripts, have been preserved to this day.
Clara wrote her texts in a very readable and carefully crafted script , which is often cited by paleographers as the prototype of the 15th-century chancellery bastarda . Last but not least, the consistent naming of scribes at the end of all codices made it possible for them to be included in the DAmalS [6] project of the Institute for German Studies at the Karl Franzens University of Graz . Medievalists there try to identify the scribes' hands of a manuscript using databases and use the Hätzler's manuscripts as a paleographic comparison option.
To date, eight of the Hätzler's manuscripts are known. In the research literature the number nine is occasionally given when the two-part manuscript of “The Holy Lives” is counted as two works. These include legal books , hunting literature, a work on the subject of mysticism and magic and the collective manuscript “Song Book”. The eight codices date from the period between 1465 and 1473, were written in a script typical of Clara Hätzlerin, namely the Chancellery Bastarda , and could undoubtedly be attributed to Clara Hätzlerin as the scribe, as she signed most of the manuscripts herself . [2]
Cyrus, Cynthia J. (2009). The scribes for women's convents in late medieval Germany. Toronto [Ont.]: University of Toronto Press. p. 55.

Dorothea von Hof (1458-1501), née Ehingerin
From the possession of Margarete Ehingerin, née Neidhart (died 1513), married since 1482 to the Constance patrician Hans Ehinger (1456–1505), son of Heinrich Ehinger and Margarete von Kappel; cf.the alliance coat of arms Ehinger/Neidhart 2r and the ownership entry 357r: This book belongs to Margreth Ehingerjn in Mergstat. Contrary to earlier opinions, it was therefore not the older Margarete Ehinger, née von Kappel (died 1490?), but rather her daughter-in-law who owned this manuscript (cf.Gebauer [2010] p. 37 f.[with family tree]); she was thus likely also the sister-in-law of the scribe, Dorothea von Hof, née Ehingerin. Regarding three other manuscripts from the possession of the older Ehinger generation, see Nos. 36.0.2. (Einsiedeln Stiftsbibliothek, Codex 710), No. 43.1.55. (Einsiedeln, Stiftsbibliothek, Codex 283), and No. 59.2.5. (St. Gallen, Kantonsbibliothek, VadSlg. Ms. 343 c–d).

Elisabeth was born in Colmar to the prominent family of Diepolt Kempf, who achieved citizenship in Colmar in 1389: her father, uncles, and grandfather all held important city offices. At the age of six, she was given to the Dominican monastery of Unterlinden. She became a nun, and later served as prioress, from 1469 until her death on 9 Oct. 1485.
      In a vita appended to the Latin Vitae sororum, Elisabeth is lauded as a translator of Latin texts into German. She translated and extended the Vitae sororum subtiliae of Katherina von Gebersweiler, adding four additional vitae and a series of miracles associated with an image of the Virgin Mary which hung on the chapel wall at Underlinden. She explains in the colophon that she translated the work for the benefit of those who could not understand Latin. Geith suggests that she was also the translator of a "Leben Jesu." The evidence that the translation is hers is found in the colophon at the end of the poem. The most likely Latin original is an unpublished "Vita Christi," recently ascribed by W. Baier to the Italian Augustine-hermit, Michael de Massa.

Little is known about Elisabeth besides that which has been gleaned from her two texts, a Vita of Irmgard von Roth, and the Kirchberg sister-book. According to the Irmgard-Vita, she entered the Dominican monastery of Kirchberg at age four-and-a-half, and may have been of Jewish heritage. She had been a nun for forty-two years, and had been Irmgard's close confidante for twenty years when she began to write.
      The process by which the Irmgard Vita came to be written was rather complicated, has similarities with the composition of the Vita of Heinrich Seuse and Mechthild von Hackeborn's Liber specialis gratiae, and is detailed at the end of the Vita. Elisabeth wrote about Irmgard's experiences in secret; at first she recorded them on a wax tablet, then she transferred them to parchment for a permanent record. Irmgard sensed that Elisabeth might be engaged in such an activity, and her suspicions culminated in a nocturnal visit to Elisabeth's bed in which Irmgard searched for the manuscript. After Elisabeth received a promise from Irmgard that she would not destroy the text, she produced it for her. At this point, Irmgard took an active interest and role in the writing process, and the two women corroborated closely on a final version of the Vita.
      Like the Vita, there are two different versions of the sister-book. The shorter, more detailed version contains twenty-three vitae, is extant in a fifteenth-century manuscript, and was edited as the sister-book of Kirchberg bei Sulz. The longer contains sixty-four abbreviated vitae, is extant in a seventeenth-century manuscript, and was edited as Kirchberg bei Haigerloch. Walter Blank contends that both versions are independent copies of the same original, now lost. Due to continuities of style and content between the two redactions of the Irmgard-Vita--there is little doubt that Elisabeth was responsible for both renditions of the Vita--and the corresponding versions of the sister-book, Siegfried Ringler believes that Elisabeth wrote both editions of that text as well.

Scholastica was elected abbess of Kloster Vinnenberg around July 19, 1547, by Bishop Franz von Waldeck, succeeding Hillegund Hoyer. During her term, the monastery church underwent two devastating fires in 1550 and 1568. She compiled a calendar and index for the monastery around 1560. She died sometime before March 26 1572, when Johann von Hoya, Bishop of Münster, appointed her successor Dorothea Peicks. (from himml: https://haf.vhmml.org/person/832310079740)
